Certainly! To add a color-burn effect to the background property with a radial gradient, you can use the CSS background-blend-mode property. Here’s an example:


.my-element {
  background: radial-gradient(circle at top right, #021, #123, #120, #121, #021);
  background-blend-mode: color-burn;
}



In the above example, the background property sets the radial gradient background with the specified colors. The background-blend-mode property is then used to apply the color-burn blending mode to the background, resulting in a color-burn effect.

You can modify the values and positioning of the radial gradient according to your preferences. Additionally, you can experiment with other blending modes (multiply, overlay, etc.) to achieve different visual effects.

