I apologize for the confusion. If you want to apply a color-burn effect to the whole background of the page, you can use a pseudo-element and absolute positioning to achieve the desired effect. Here's an example:

body {
  position: relative;
}

body::before {
  content: "";
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  left: 0;
  background: radial-gradient(circle at top right, #021, #123, #120, #121, #021);
  mix-blend-mode: color-burn;
  z-index: -1;
}

In the above example, we create a pseudo-element (::before) that covers the entire body of the page using absolute positioning. The background property is set to the radial gradient you provided, and mix-blend-mode is set to color-burn to apply the desired blending effect.

Ensure that the body element has enough height (e.g., by setting min-height: 100vh) for the pseudo-element to cover the entire background.

